{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c141d852-98cd-4d08-88c5-2f32fd92dff4","content":"\n\nHere's how to connect your C# MCP server to the **MCP Inspector**:\n\n### 1. Run the Inspector\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (usually at `http://localhost:6274`).\n\n### 2. Configure the connection\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourMcpServer.csproj`\n\nOr if you have a published binary:\n\n- **Command:** `/path/to/YourMcpServer`\n\n### 3. Click **Connect**\n\nThe Inspector will spawn your server as a child process, communicate over stdin/stdout, and display available tools, prompts, and resources.\n\n### Debugging tips\n\n- **Don't write to stdout** in your server for anything other than MCP JSON-RPC messages — use `stderr` for logs (`Console.Error.WriteLine`).\n- Add `--no-build` to args if you've already built, to speed up startup.\n- If your server needs env vars, set them in the **Environment Variables** section of the Inspector UI.\n- To attach a debugger, add a `Debugger.Launch()` call or set `DOTNET_ENVIRONMENT=Development` and use `dotnet run` with `--launch-profile` that has `\"commandLineArgs\": \"--debug\"`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"eeb6bc5c-a187-4d44-a72e-7984842468c9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to connect a C# MCP server (using stdio transport) to the MCP Inspector for interactive testing/debugging. This is a knowledge question — I can answer directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":397},"id":"fbfec98f-7b5d-4363-ae12-af09b982a232","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:53:16.968Z","parentId":"fb590d2e-22bf-404a-90c8-110b665ea60a"}
